%N A390642 a(n) is the smallest integer k such that the number of sums a(i) + a(j) <= k for i <= j < n is less than k - n + 1.
%C A390642 Erdős asks if the number of solutions a(i) + a(j) <= k is equal to k + O(k^(1/4+o(1))) (see Erdős Problems link).
%C A390642 Conjecture: a(n) ~ Pi/8 * n^2.
%H A390642 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/954">Problem 954</a>, Erdős Problems.
%e A390642 a(3) = 5 because k = 5 is the least integer such that the number of sums for the first two terms {1, 3} that are less than 5 is 2: 1 + 1 = 2 and 3 + 1 = 4 and 2 is less than 5 - 3 + 1.
%t A390642 a[1]=1;a[n_]:=a[n]=(k=0;pos=0;s=Sort@Flatten[Table[a[i]+a[j],{j,n-1},{i,j}]];While[True,While[pos<Length@s&&s[[pos+1]]<=k,pos++];If[pos<k-n+1,Break[]];k++;];k);Array[a,55]
